{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_hugo_ver01/data/sn85042303/00200295419/1920092101/0161.xml":{"full_text":"St-\nt t\nr\nPAGE FOUR\nDAILY ARDMOREITE\nutJSDAY, SEPTEMBER 21, 1920.\nDaily Ardmoreite\nArOmore, Oklahoma.\nvJobn F. Easley Editor and Qene.al\nManager.\nGeorge H. Wyutt. Managing Editor\nc- lira. Emmitt T. Reid City Editor.\nAfUrnoonj (Except Saturday) and\nSunday Morning.\nFull Leased Associated Press Wirs\nEntered at Ardmore, Okla., PostoIici\nas SecondClass Mall.\n4i TELEPHONES\ntf Editorial Department\nlOty Lditor\nSociety Editor\n579\n...5S1\nm\nBUSINESS PHONES.\n'Circulation\neBusiness Offlc\nAdver.'islng Department\n.25\nS\n5\n1 MEMBER ASSOCLVTED PRESS\ny The Asscclated Press la exclusively\nc entitled to the use for republication of\nall news dispatches credited to or not\n-otherwise credited in this paper and\nalso the local news published herein.\nTUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 21. 1920\nThe first and most obvious dis\ntinction between observation and\nexperiment is, that the latter is\nan immense extension of the form\ner. John Stuart Mill.\n1 AM RIGHT, AS YOU SEE!\"\nCongrtsman Harreld is making a\nsweeping campaign over Oklahoma in\nthe Interests of his race against Scott\nFerris for the United States senator\njshlp, and playing up to the \"dis\ngruntled\" element, doing his best, as\n1 a good Republican, to muke the vot\ners believe, if they are Democrats,\nthat ihey should \"vote for the man.\"\n;but telling them that \"the man\" will\nI be found In the ranks of Kcpub-\nlicanlsm.\nMade into a synopsis, boiled down\n!vith all unnecessary purts of speech\nliuii: atcd, the story i f the creation\nof the world by the Republican party\nomitted, the conquest of the nations cf\nlhc Old East by Xerxes, under the\n-'direction of the Republican senators,\nleft out, Mr. Harreld's speeches nar\nrow down to the naked statement, \"I\nrim right, us you all sec\nIn a speech recently delivered by\nMr. Harreld, at Madili a d several\nI other places, he called particular at\n1 ti ntlon to the fact that he had been\napproached in the matter of securing\na tetter and a uniform price for cot\nton. He stated, we ire Informed,\nthat he had Investlgat.-d the matter\nthoroughly ana felt Mtlsfled that\neverything W;is being don in the\ni matter which t was possible to do.\nWe suppose that a reporter, had\nere have been present JaUir.g a ver\nbatum report cf the sirwh, would\nhave here Inserted the votd, paren\nthetically, \"applluse..\"\nSo fur ns reports, received from\nthose who have listened In Mr. Hnr\nleid, ISs spevrhes. eo:icy Intelli\ngenre relative to his elucidation of\nthe live Issues of the day nnd consist\nIn maintaining a stern and steadfast\nsilence relative to his vote on the\nmatter of seating Berger, when even\nthe most reactionary nml stalwarts\nof all the reactionary and stalwarts\nheld thnt Ttorger wns unfitted to si.\nIn the halls of congress nnd consort\nWith respeotnblc Americans. In ad\ndition' to this they also bear out re\npeated nnd Impressive statements to\nthe effect that \"I nm right upon my\nstand upon the Issues before us,\"\nbut fall lamentably In producing nr-\nguments fnr or ngalnst those Issues.\nThe state of Oklahoma Is entitled\nto a man In the senate of the United\nStates who Is ns able nnd as well\nqualified ns Is Robert I.. Owen nnd\nwho Is, above nil else an American.\nft man who holds to American Ideas\nand to American Ideals.\nThe Ardmoreite asks the honest\nand fnlr-mlnded voter the honest nnd\n'fair-minded question 'Is Harreld such\nFolks who want the best\nmust insist upon getting\nwhat they ask for.\nTo be sure of the best in\ncorn flakes.order\nPostToasties\nNo corn flakes com\npare with them in flavor,\nfullness, goodness.\nTry a package and make\nyour own decision.\nThat's fair; isrit it?\nAll grocers sell\nPostToasties\nMada by\nPotum Cral Co.,Inc,\nBattlo Crek,Mich.\na man? Does Harreld meet with your\nIdeas of a statesman? Do you think\nAmericanism prompted his vote in\nthe Berger matter?\"\nSHOW THEM WHAT YOU ARE\nThe Republicans are putting' forth\nan organized effort to carry Okluhoma\nat the ensuing general election or,\nfailing in that, to make a big show\ning at the polls by both Increasing\ntheir vote and decreasing the Demo\ncratic majority.\nV\nIn their efforts to do this the cam\npaign managers of the G. O. P., In\nthis state, working In conjunction\nwith the Republican newspapers, are\nleaving no stones unturned, are over\nlooking no bets and are doing their\nd dest to create a disgruntled feeling\nin the breasts of those whose De\nmocracy Is only skin-deep. Republi\ncan speakers, Republican chairmen,\nRepublican committeemen and Re\npublican committeemen and Republi\ncan editors, with a few Republican\npreachers joining in the Doxology are\ntalking and writing and telling about\nthe \"sore spots\" found on Democrats\nwho supported Senator Gore in the\nlate primaries. These Republicans\nare telling you that many, very many\nDemocrats who supported Gore are\nso sore that they will either vote the\nstraight Republican ticket, this fall,\nor else vote that part of the Republi\ncan ticket which carries Mr. Harreld's\nname. v\nThe utter untruth of this statement\nwas voiced by. a good, old Democ-nt\nbrother over In Marshall county, a\nf.'w days ago. This man was one of\nthe true Democrats who voted for\nMr. Core In the primary. And as n\ntrue Democrat he will now vote for\nMr. Ferris in the general election.\nIn speaking of the matter of the\nrace between Ferris, Democrat, find\nto a Republican who Importuned him\nliarreld, Republican, this man replied\nto vote for Harreld, playing nt the\ntime upon his support .of flore, and\nsaid, after listening to the anti-Ferris\narguments for a few minutes, \"Hell,\nMan, I'm a Democrat.\"\nIf every Democrat in Oklahoma\nwill come out as did this man, open\nend above board, and let the Republi\ncan who tries to make medicine with\nhim know Just what he Is and where\nhe stands, the work of spreading antl\nD?morratic propaganda and anti\nDemocrat poison will stop.\nTell them, when they come to you,\nwhat you are; Bhow them, when you\nlio to vote, what you are, and the\nmorning after the general election\nwill show Oklahoma still In the Demo\ncrat column, with a safe and sound\nmajority.\nThere Is no reason why Scott\nFerris, or any other Democrat should\nbe defeated In this state. On the\nother hand there is every reason\nwhy he should be elected.\nPROLONGED DEPRESSION\nIMPROBABLE\nThe September bulletin of the Na\ntional City Rank, In discussing the\nbusiness outlook, expresses the opin\nion that no prolonged depression is\nprobable. The bulletin says:\n\"Over the Industrial field the gen\nera! trend of prices Is downward\nand the pressure Is slackening, with\nan Increase of unemployment. An\nnbundance of labor was available for\nthe harvest, and It Is probable that\nsome of the labor which has been at\ntracted from the farms during the\nlist five years will now return and\nremain. The period of acute scarcity\nboth for goods nnd for labor appears\nto be over and a competitive situa\ntion 'n developing. It Is well that\nthere shall be general recognition of\nthe fact that the upward movement\nhas run Its course Rnd that further\nwae and price advances are untimely.\n\"It does not necessarily follow, how\never, that the very pessimistic prog\nnostications nre Justified. It was a\nmistake when the war ended to -think\nthat an Immediate readjustment upon\na lower level of values would bo ef\nfected; there was a grent shortage of\ngoods and a backed-up demand for\nlabor which promptly absorbed nil\nthnt was released from the armies\nand wnr Industries. Hence the quick\nrevival of business nnd the rise of\nwages and prices In 1919. That situ\nation was as abnormal and as tem\nporary in character as the Industrial\nsituation of the war time. Numerous\nsigns of relaxation are now appear\ning, but it is likely to prove as great\na mistake now as in the early months\nof 1919 to think that a period of gen\neral nnd prolonged depression Is at\nhand. There still Is a great amount\nof work In arrears, and an impera\ntive need for construction work and\nfor the production of goods to satisfy\nthe wants of our people as well as\nof the rest of the world.\"\nThe only comment that need be\nmade on this Is' that since the bulletin\nwas written about three weeks ago,\nthere already is a noticeable revival\nin a number of lines. How soon\ngeneral revival may be looked for re\nmains to be seen, but there Is every\nreason for conservative optimism and\nnone whatever for pessimism. Fort\nWorth Star-Telegram.\nThere may not be a hell, but if\nthere Is not then there should be one.\nJust think of a fellow turning his\nhose loose on his weed-grown lawn\nwhile the water problem remains un\nsolved. It seems that railway companies\nare resenting the stand taken by\nthe newspapers which tell the truth,\nrelative to the Inadequate service\nwhich Is still being peddled to the\npublic, hike In fares to the contrary,\nnotwithstanding.\nMrs. Robertson, \"first lady of the\nstate,\" will meet with the lady Demo\ncrats of Ardmore tomorrow evening.\nTou have to hand it to them, boys.\nThe women voters nre better organ\nized than are the men, nnd they\nmean business. We nre betting on\nthe Democracy in petticoats to in\ncrease Oklahoma's Democratic ma\njority,\nSpeaking of \"improved\" railway\nservice. Why Is It thnt the Frisco\ntime card routes passengers from\nArdmore out of bed and away without\nbreakfast, and then carries them down\nto Madlll and maroons them on the\nside-track for 20 minutes? That\n\"spot\" time, used at Ardmore would\ngive a fellolr a chance to swallow\ntwo eggs and a cup of coffee.\n\nThe Ardmoreite can boast of hav\ning one of two things a reporter who\nis the best single-handed, long-distance\nliar in Oklahoma, or some\nfellow who is a past master In the\nare of \"lifting\" cigar boxes. N..B.\nThe cigars were in the box at the\ntime, all of them, a full fifty, each\none with a gilt band about Its abdo\nmen. Just what is a 'honker\" put on\nan automobile for, nnyway? So far\nas we can note, taking the Ardmore\nautos as a sample, there Is no earthly\nuse for the horn. Just open your cut\nout and let her go and you will make\nnoise enough. If you honk your\nhonker someone may hear you coming\nand deprive you ,of the pleasure of\nrunning over him.\nEditorial\nof the Day\nFINANCING THE FARM.\n(Enid News.)\nThat the banker can help the\nfarmer was convincingly set forth\nby Dean Vivian of Ohio State Univers\nity in an address to the Michigan\nBankers' association in which he told\nof what had already been done In the\nfinancing of stock-breeding clubs of\nfarm lads and co-operation with agri\ncultural colleges, county farm bureaus\nand county agents. These nre the\nchief agencies which will he'p the\nfarmer to Incrense production. It is\npart of the bankers' business to help\nthe farmer to money and In the prop\ner use of that money. With such a\ntriumvirate the farmer, the scientific\nagencies and the financial men of af\nfairsthere Is no reason why the\nbusiness of farming should not be Im\nproved, made to yield a greater re\nturn and Insure the country against\nunnecessary waste and destruction.\nDetailing the possibilities of help\nfulness, Dr. Vivian suggested that the\nbanker, being by virtue of his busi\nness a community leader, should lenrn\nthe agricultural needs of the locality\nand then encourage the farmer to In\nvest to tho economic limit in that\nwhich will Improve his farm and en\nhoncn his business. It may be drain\nage that Is most needed, or It may\nbe stock ot n better breed, or It\nmay be some other of a numher of\nthings. Whatever it Is, the progressive\nbanker will discover It by consulta\ntion with those who know and will\nthen give to the farmer the benefit\nof his larirer knowledge of sound fin\nancing. Increasing the prosperity of\nthe farms ,thn rpenker said, helps not\nonly the farmer, but nlso the banker,\nsince It cn'arges his business, while\nloaning money outside of the com\nmunity actively promotes the business\nof neither. thrives the community\nso thrives the bnnk.\nThe counsel Is wise. It applies the\nold truth that the tnun who knows\nhow to work with those about him Is\nthe man who wins nnd that he who\nhelps his fellows Is the reul community\nleaden Wherever we live, we all want\nthe farmer to succeed In business for\nupon that success depends our food\nsupply,\nDEATH BREAKS TRIAN\n(il'LAIt CHAIN OF CF.N.\nTF.NAKIAN I! MOTHERS\nP.elfust, Ireland. Pi-pt. 21. A unique\nrecord nf centenarian brothers has\nJust been broken by the death of\nJohn Mullan, Aged 101, who lived with\nhis brother Henry, aged 10) nt Doney\ndule, near Dungannon.\nKansas City. Ry splitting even In\na doublehender with Ploux City yes\nterdny, Tulsa won the 1920 Western\nLeague pennnnt. Had Tulsa lost both\ngames, Wichita would hnve been wln\nner as the latter club took both\nends ot a double hVfldcr (rum Omaha.\nTHE IMPOSSIBLE\nMatthew 12-9 to 1J\n(A sermon preached by Rev. C. C.\nWeith. Sunday night).\nJesus was always watched and criti\ncized by those opposed to Him. He\ninterfered with their plans. He was\nnot orthodox. He thought more of\nthe people's needs than of the good\nwill of the leaders. When He en\ntered the synagogue He was nt once\nlinked with the man In need. Would\nHe dare to break precedent nnd cus\ntom and heal on \"the Sabbath? Yes\nhe would.\nHe saw the man's withered hand,\nthe man's need, Bird Instantly offered\nthe relief of a perfect cure. \"Stretch\nforth thy hand.\" AVhy, could he? It\nwas a helpless, useless hand. He\nhad not been able to use It for years.\nIt was withered and the sinews\nshrunken. He could, he stretched it\nforth. This is common sense nnd\nreason: After ull, reason Is not the\nonly power of man. We do more\nthings spontaneously than we do\nby mere reason. The defective man\nnever stopped to reason. He saw\nthose compelling eyes and under\ntheir spell he acted Instantly. What\nan amazing thing this 1st The 1m\npossib'e has happened. The man\nmoved his useless, Immovable hand.\nIt cannot be done! Yet, he did It.\nHerein Is a thought of man's power\nwhen Joined to Clod's.\nCourage and Self-Reliance Essential\nToo many of us nre content to sit\nor lie helpless when we could help\nourselves. Look at the beggars on\nour streets. Many of them are beg\ngars from choice rather than from\nneed. We all know of people who\nwere blind yet were not content to\nbeg hut made themselves useful. Oth\ners who have lost one or both limbs\nyet did not give tip. Courage nnd self\nreliance are essential to a successful\nlife and especially so to a Christian\nlife.\nGod All Powerful\nChrist can help us to overcome\nour defects. Have you a withered\nhand? Take it to Jesus. Many really\nhonest people are afraid to become\nChristians because they fear they\nwill not be able to hold out. \"I don't\nwant to start nnd fall.\" \"I know\nmy weakness nnd fear It will come\nback.\" The fallacy lies In not taking\nGod Into account here, nod Is all\npowerful and your friend. A real\nfriend will not fail In the hour of\nneed, neither will God. Besides, we\nYou\ni t l\no;:o\nGoodrich Tires today are\nsold by dealers everywhere\nat a lower price than in 1910\nand what is more to the\npoint in this comparison,\nGoodrich Tires in 1920 give\non the average nearly double\nthe number of miles pertire.\nThe Goodrich adjustment\nbasis of 8,000 miles for Sil\nvertowns and 6,000 miles\nfor Fabrics at today's prices\ngives motorists twice the\nmileage at less cost per tire\nThe comparative table below will\ntell you why Goodrich Trn ere a\ngood buy today.\nFABRIC\nosldjustment 'Basis:\nSilvertown Cords\n8ooo Utiles\nFabric Tires\n6oooJLfj7j\nGojodir\nourselves are really stronger than\nwe think, If we really try.\nThe man with the withered hand\nknew his need and obeyed at once.\nAll Things Possible\nIt Is a curious fact that the arm\ndid not get well by degrees. It was\ninstantly restored and made whole\nlike the other. Do you suppose the\nman wns fearful of a relapse? No.\nHe did not expect the disease to\nreturn. That would not, be trusting\nthe Christ. So the timid doubter\nmay realize that a powerful Christ\nIs his helper and that to Clod all\nthings are possible. We really need\ngreater faith In our own powers and\nalso in the love and power of our\nGod.\nTHE OPEN SHOP\nOrganized Labor Claim Movement\nHampers Growth of Cilies.\nOkmulgee Okla Sept. 21. A decla\nration that tho forces of reaction In\nthe United States, opposed to progres\nsive legislation nnd policies In Ameri\ncan politics realizing that the forces\nof organized labor was the greatest In\nstrument for tho fostering of legisla\ntion In the Interest of all the people,\nhad begun a systematic campaign to\npoison tho minds of the public against\na'l organized labor and convince it\nthat labor organizations were vicious,\nfeatured the address of Edgar Fcnton,\npresident of the Oklahoma Federation\nof Labor at its opening here Monday\nin annual convention. President Fen\nton declared that tho open shop move\nment throughout the southwest had\nseriously hampered the progress of\nmany growing Oklahoma cities as well\nas In other states.\nLineman Hilled at Plcher.\nMInmi, Okla., Sept. 21 Glenn Price,\n32 years old, a resident of Baxter\nSprings Kansas, employed as a line\nman for an electric company wns\nInstantly killed near Plcher Satur\nday afternoon when he grasped a wire\ncarrying high voltage current. He was\nunmarried.\nParis. League of nations, through\nits Intervention In the Aland Islands,\na question between Finland and Swe\nden has proposed Its right to live as\nJan effective means of preventing wars.\nHJalmar Granting, prime minisetr ot\nSweden,\nRio Janeiro. King Albert ajid Queen\nElizabeth of Belgium, the first king\nto visit any South American ccun\ntry received a tremendous ovation\ncan buy\nr\nm\ntoday at an average of\n25 less than in 1910\nTIRE PRICES\nSIZE I9IQ TODAY\n3QX3 25AS I9.IO\n303 33.05 23.10\n32x4 48.65 36.00\n34x4 65.35 S3.B\n35x5 $2.75 65.35\n'leii\nTRANSPORT YANKEE\nDAVY JONES' LOCKER\nNew Bedford, Mass., Sept. 21. The\ncruiser Yankee, which was wrecked on\nHen and Chickens reef In Buzzards Bay\nI! years ago and which sank and was\nrefloated only to go down again after\nniiftlng a few miles, has been finally\nlost to the navy. Wreckers who have\nbeen trying for seevral years to re\nmove the hulk of the sunken cruiser\nas a menace to navigation have\nblown It up, and timbers of the old\nYankee are now scattered on the\nfloor of the bay.\nThe Yankee, which was formerly\nthe coastwise passenger steamer El Sud\nwns In transport service during the\nSpanish-American war nnd was con\ntinued on the naval rolls afterward\nits cruiser. She went nground on\nHen and Chickens, during a thick fog\non t no nirht of September 23, 1908,\nand slipped off Into deep water.\nThe nnvy's attempt to float her,\nmade under the direction of naval\nconstructor Washington L. Capps,\nfailed, and private bids were called\nfor. As a result, the first notable\nuse of compressed air for marine\nsalvage In this country was made\nby John Arbuckle, of New York, a\nsugar refiner. He bought Peary's\nArctic ship, Roosevelt, nnd made her\nthe headquarters of his operations.\nAfter three months work with the\nIf the -children get it, don't take\nrhancrs with unknown prepara\ntions, but eive them this absolutely\nreliable remedy at once. Oste\nins free from calomel.\nTh Doctor' Prttcription\n60c at AH Dealers.\nf2\nf ffest in the Long Run\ncompressed air method the Yankee\nwas raised and started in low lor\nthis port.\nShe ran Into a storm during the\nnight, heavy seas thumped her weak\nened frame and one of the air porta\nbroke. The Yankee went down again\noff Dumpling Light and, although the\nArbuckle wreckers renewed their ef\nforts, and other salvage outfits did\ntheir best to bring her to the top,\nshe stayed there for 10 years before\nshe was blown to pieces.\nTELEPHONE DIRECTORIES.\nNEW TELEPHONE DIRECTORY\nWILL GO TO PRESS SOON;; AR\nRANGE FOR CHANGES, FULL\nFACE TYPE AND ADVERTISE\nMENT AT ONCE. SOUTHWESTERN\nBELL TELEPHONE CO. Adv. -.20-3\nm\nUse Ardmoreite Want Ads. for quick\nresults.\nNEW AUTOMOBILE\nFOR SALE AT A\nBARGAIN\nThrough a mortgage fore\nclosure I have for sale a\nbrand new seven-passenger\nNational Touring car. The\nnew 1920 Sextet model. U.\nS. cord tires and fully\nequipped. The list price on\nthis car is $4100, F. 0. B.\nOklahoma City. The car has\nnever been run. Price for\nimmediate sale $3300, net.\nCar can be seen in Oklaho\nma City. Call or write Fred\nS. Goldstandt, 1203 Colcord\nBldg., Oklahoma City, Okla.\nPhone Walnut 905.\n1\nires","height":"30068","width":"19860"}}
